\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Most obvious method is to find roots of characteristic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\vec{A}}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

, but it is very ill-conditioned
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Another idea is power iteration, using fact that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\vec{x}}{\Vert\vec{x}\Vert},\frac{\vec{A}\vec{x}}{\Vert\vec{A}\vec{x}\Vert},\frac{\vec{A}^{2}\vec{x}}{\Vert\vec{A}^{2}\vec{x}\Vert},\frac{\vec{A}^{3}\vec{x}}{\Vert\vec{A}^{3}\vec{x}\Vert},\dots
\]

\end_inset

 converge to an eigenvector corresponding to the largest eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A}$
\end_inset

 in absolute value, but it may converge very slowly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instead, compute a eigenvalue-revealing factorization, such as Schur factorizati
on 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{A}=\vec{Q}\vec{T}\vec{Q}^{*}
\]

\end_inset

by introducing zeros, using algorithms similar to 
\begin_inset Formula $QR$
\end_inset

 factorization
\end_layout

\end_deeper
