status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A Fundamental Difficulty
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
However, eigenvalue-revealing factorization cannot be done in finite number
 of steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
Any eigenvalue solver must be iterative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To see this, consider a general polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(z)=z^{n}+a_{n-1}z^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}z+a_{0}
\]

\end_inset

There is no closed-form expression for roots for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>4$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In general, the roots of polynomial equations higher than fourth degree
 cannot be written in terms of a finite number of operations (Abel, 1842)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A Fundamental Difficulty Cont'd
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
However, the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\vec{A}}$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of the 
\emph on
companion matrix
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{A}=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
0 &  &  &  & -a_{0}\\
1 & 0 &  &  & -a_{1}\\
 & 1 & \ddots &  & \vdots\\
 &  & \ddots & 0 & -a_{n-2}\\
 &  &  & 1 & -a_{n-1}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, in general, we cannot find the eigenvalues of a matrix in a finite
 number of steps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice, however, there are algorithms that converge to desired precision
 in a few iterations
\end_layout

\end_deeper
